                <property name="tooltip-text" translatable="yes">Floyd’s Algorithm is a dynamic programming method used to find the shortest paths between all pairs of vertices in a weighted graph.
It works by gradually improving an initial distance matrix, which at first simply contains the direct edge weights between vertices (or infinity if no direct edge exists).
The algorithm then considers each vertex in turn as a possible intermediate point along a path, checking if routing through that vertex yields a shorter distance between any pair of nodes.
By systematically applying this update rule for every possible intermediate vertex, Floyd’s Algorithm ensures that, after n iterations (where n is the number of vertices), the matrix contains the shortest path distances between all pairs.</property>
